[[Image:Father time 7765.jpg|thumb|1897 Baby New Year with [[Father Time]]]] [[Image:Babynew.jpg|thumb|1908 Baby New Year on the cover of ''[[The Saturday Evening Post]]''.]] The '''Baby New Year''' is a [[personification]] of the start of the [[New Year]] commonly seen in [[editorial cartoons]]. He symbolizes the "birth" of the next year and the "passing" of the prior year; in other words, a "rebirth".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.novareinna.com/festive/bny.html|title=Baby New Year|website=www.novareinna.com}}</ref> Baby New Year's purpose varies by myth, but he generally performs some sort of ceremonial duty over the course of his year such as [[Wiktionary:chronicle#Noun|chronicling]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://sendables.jibjab.com/originals/2008_year_in_review|title=JibJab|website=sendables.jibjab.com}}</ref> the year's events or presiding over the year as a [[figurehead|symbol]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.antiqueshoppefl.com/newimages/newyearsbaby2.jpg |title=Saturday Evening Post cover |website=www.antiqueshoppefl.com |format=PDF}}</ref>
==Legend== The myth most associated with him is that he is a baby at the beginning of his year, but Baby New Year quickly ages until he is elderly (like [[Father Time]], with whom he is often associated<ref>{{cite web|url=http://themoderatevoice.com/25364/una-vez-mas-the-old-man-and-the-baby-of-new-years-iconology-a-lost-story/|title=Una Vez Más: The Old Man and The Baby of New Year's Iconology: A Lost Story – The Moderate Voice|website=themoderatevoice.com}}</ref>) at the end of his year. Very rarely is the Baby New Year depicted as any age other than a baby or as a very old man. Some stories, especially those with depictions of years past, will have him [[personification|bear a strong likeness]] to key events in his time.<ref name="Rudolph's Shiny New Year">[[Rudolph's Shiny New Year]]; https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0073640/</ref> At this point, he hands over his duties to the next Baby New Year, while he either dies or remains in this state and retires.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://themoderatevoice.com/wordpress-engine/wp-content/dr-e/old-man-baby-new-year.jpg |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2011-03-25 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110208194253/http://themoderatevoice.com/wordpress-engine/wp-content/dr-e/old-man-baby-new-year.jpg |archivedate=2011-02-08 }}</ref>
==Representation== The [[stereotype|stereotypical]] representation of Baby New Year is as a baby boy wearing nothing more than a [[diaper]], a [[top hat]] and a [[sash]] across his torso that shows the year he is representing (e.g. 2013).<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.nma.tv/father-time-2010-baby-year-2011-battle/ |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2011-03-25 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110104182324/http://www.nma.tv/father-time-2010-baby-year-2011-battle/ |archivedate=2011-01-04 |df= }}</ref><ref name="Rudolph's Shiny New Year"/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.marthastewart.com/good-thing/baby-new-year|title=Baby New Year|date=2 February 2011|publisher=}}</ref> He is sometimes depicted holding or associated with an [[hourglass]], a [[Party horn|noisemaker]], or other item either pertaining to time or New Year's Day festivities. Often, he is not a complete [[newborn]] but instead more closely resembles a [[toddler]], because he is frequently shown standing on his own, crawling or barely walking, or having a small amount of (usually blond) hair.
==Baby New Year title== In addition to being a mythical figure, the title of "Baby New Year" is sometimes given to living people. The first baby born in any village or city in a certain year may be honored by being labeled as the official Baby New Year for that year.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.jhnewsandguide.com/article.php?art_id=6852|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110930032840/http://www.jhnewsandguide.com/article.php?art_id=6852|archivedate=2011-09-30|title=Jackson Hole News&Guide; - Baby New Year born at home with midwife, family|date=30 September 2011|publisher=}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.wlfi.com/dpp/news/local/lafayette-welcomes-new-years-baby |title=Archived copy |access-date=2011-03-25 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110105113535/http://www.wlfi.com/dpp/news/local/lafayette-welcomes-new-years-baby |archive-date=2011-01-05 |dead-url=yes |df= }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.boston.com/section/news|title=The latest Boston, local and national news|first=|last=john-waller|date=11 January 2016|website=Boston.com}}</ref> The official Baby New Year can be male or female, even though the mythical Baby New Year is nearly always male. Attempts to name an official Baby New Year for an entire country have sometimes been made, but generally there are multiple contenders and no single Baby New Year can be confirmed. There has however been a great deal of several who have come close. Numerous hospitals no longer make a Baby New Year public due to concerns that the infant will become a target for criminals.<ref>[http://www.kvoa.com/news/first-baby-of-2015-it-s-a-secret-in-many-places/ First baby of 2015? It's a secret in many places] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150101054607/http://www.kvoa.com/news/first-baby-of-2015-it-s-a-secret-in-many-places/ |date=2015-01-01 }}. ''Associated Press''. Retrieved December 31, 2014. </ref>
==Popular culture== * Baby New Year is featured in the TV special ''[[Rudolph's Shiny New Year]]''. The featured Baby New Year is named Happy who goes missing before New Year's Eve and Rudolph had to travel to the Archipelago of Last Years (a bunch of islands where the old years go to retire) to find him before a [[vulture]] named Aeon the Terrible gets to him in order to keep the year from ending and stop time, thus preventing his predestined death. Happy ran away due to being laughed at because of his big ears which he wears under his top hat. Rudolph shows Happy his nose and tells him his own story of being shunned because of his nonconformity before asking Happy to let him see his ears. After Happy's ears played a part in defeating Aeon the Terrible, Happy is returned to Father Time as the year "Nineteen-Wonderful" begins.<ref name="Rudolph's Shiny New Year"/> * A parody of Baby New Year, given the name "Big Fat Baby," appears in the animated series ''[[Histeria!]]''
